commit.message:
Release v0.5.2

This release includes the following fixes:

* Always return an integer error code from exit_code()
* Fix line buffering detection for TTYs on Illumos/Solaris
* Numerous improvements to the integration tests:
  - Work correctly with less v633
  - Fix flaky tests
  - Improve behaviour and debugging when tests fail
  - Allow test runners to capture stdout of all child processes
* Update test dependencies to account for recent releases of fixtures
* Test using a more recent version of mypy
* Run tests on Python 3.11 and 3.12

Fix tty line buffering detection on Illumos

On Illumos (and presumably Solaris), fseek() doesn't return an error
when called on a TTY, contrary to the Solaris man page for e.g.
fflush(), which states that TTYs are not seekable. Consequently, in
Python the seekable() method returns True. This is not the case on
Linux, where fseek() on a TTY results in an error.

To ensure line buffering is correctly enabled on TTY inputs (and prevent
unit test failures), check that the input stream is not a TTY if it
claims to be seekable.

Fixes #4

Revert "integration tests: Reduce sleep()s"

It turns out that this sleep must have been needed, because going
without it seems to have been the cause of the flakiness of tests.

This reverts commit 95b57abb6e4b957b4e72b7b89c5f1c06b719f3a1.

Fix integration tests with less >= v613

The behaviour of less when interrupting an input stream with less than a
screenful of data changed subtly in v610 with
https://github.com/gwsw/less/commit/953257f, and later again in v613
with https://github.com/gwsw/less/commit/9d23e5c. This caused the
InvokePagerTest::test_short_streaming_output test to fail.

Where previously less printed the ':' prompt before redrawing the screen
in this scenario, it no longer does. The PagerControl code recognised
the ':' as indicating the end of the output, and prevented the
subsequent redraw being recounted as new ouput. This change ensures that
the redraw will always be counted as the end of the current output.

This means that the integration tests can handle the output given by
either of the releases v608 or v633.

Fixes #5

integration tests: Print output for easier debugging

If an assertion fails in an integration test, print the list of lines
seen in the output from the pager, both before and after parsing, to
help with debugging.
Test with Python 3.12

integration tests: Make timeouts more robust

Ensure that if the test process does not exit, we'll still open the
FIFOs in the "shell" process so that the parent process does not block
forever.
integration tests: Use constant for child pid

integration tests: Ignore sys.stdout when getting tty

After pty.fork(), in the child process it's always the file descriptor 1
that is the controlling tty. This is true even if the test runner
substitutes its own file descriptor for stdout. Therefore, make
ourselves more independent of the test runner by ignoring sys.stdout and
always using the original file descriptor.

integration tests: Prevent hang when tests fail

In the child process, we must open the FIFOs with the opposite
Read/Write sense compared to the parent.

tox: Fix dependencies for py36 environment

Ensure the pip version is at least 19.0, because this is required to use
pyproject.toml instead of a setup.py file to install the package to be
tested.

Also explicitly install testtools, because versions of pip prior to 19.0
don't appear to support extras, and thus the fixtures[streams]
dependency doesn't work. pip isn't updated until after all of the
dependencies are installed, and there isn't currently a (working) way to
update it earlier.
Use more recent mypy
Fix signal handler type in unit tests
Handle non-integer SystemExit codes

tox: pin python version for mypy

The latest Python version supported by mypy 0.8.x is 3.9.
README: fix module paths

Depend on fixtures[streams] for tox tests

The fixtures project has created a new [streams] extra, without which
the required testtools dependency does not get installed.
Test on Python 3.11

Release v0.5.1

This release makes unit tests more robust on Python 3.10.

integration tests: Increase timeout for subprocess to exit

This seems to resolve some flakiness on Python 3.10.

Release v0.5.0

This release features:

* Testing on Python 3.10.
* More (optional) strategies for selecting the pager command to use.
* Fully-automated integration testing.
* Support for type checking by consumers using PEP561.
Update installation instructions for distros
Eliminate another unnecessary type cast
Eliminate unnecessary type cast

Allow consumers to do type checking

PEP561 requires a library to include a 'py.typed' file to indicate that
it is suitable for type checking.
Add type annotations to unit tests
Add type checking for test utilities

integration tests: Add tests for piped output

Test the scenarios where the output is not to the console, but rather
piped to some other process (redirecting to a file should be
equivalent).

integration tests: Reduce sleep()s

This sleep was apparently needed only after sending Ctrl-C, so don't
sleep after every write to the pseudo-terminal.

integration tests: Use spawn instead of fork

Run the test process launched by multiprocessing in a fresh process
rather than one forked from the child process. This means that there is
no other extraneous stuff around to clean up.

In future this will allow us to reproduce bugs where buffers were left
unflushed at interpreter shutdown (such as the one fixed by
8780cac5142327cf11c8bd83dd69efccb10902f3).
